===HIV/AIDS=== {{main article|HIV/AIDS in Bhutan}}
In 2011, there were 246 reported cases of [[HIV]] in [[Bhutan]], representing just over 0.03% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhutanobserver.bt/ministry-health-detected/ |title=The Ministry of Health has Detected… |publisher=[[Bhutan Observer]] online |date=2011-08-01 |accessdate=2011-11-21}}</ref> In July 2010, there were a total of 217 cases detected, however Health Ministry sources indicated actual numbers were estimated at more than 500 by [[UNAIDS]].<ref name=update>{{cite web |url=http://www.health.gov.bt/doph/cdd/update_HIV2010.pdf |format=PDF |title=An Update on Human Immuno Deficiency Virus/Acquired Immuno Deficiency Syndrome (HIV/AIDS) |date=2010-07-01 |accessdate=2011-11-22 |publisher=Bhutan Ministry of Health |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508032703/http://www.health.gov.bt/doph/cdd/update_HIV2010.pdf |archivedate=2012-05-08 |df= }}</ref>
Through July 2010, there had been a total of 40 deaths due to HIV/AIDS-related causes, and one suicide.<ref name=update/>
==Education== As of 2017, Bhutan has a [[literacy rate]] of 71.4 percent (up from 59.5 percent in 2005). The highest literacy rate is observed in [[Thimpu]] at 83.9 percent, followed by [[Trongsa]] (77.2 percent) and [[Chukha]] (75.1 percent), while [[Gasa District|Gasa]] has the lowest rate with 59.8 percent of its population being literate.<ref> KuenselOnline [http://www.kuenselonline.com/bhutans-population-is-735553/]</ref>
