e has figures for more than one year, only the most recent figure is used (with notes for exceptional circumstances).
In the former [[Eastern Bloc]] countries, the public sector in 1989 accounted for between 70% to over 90% of total employment.<ref name="WB14b">{{Cite book|authors=Omar S. Arias, Carolina Sánchez-Páramo, María E. Dávalos, Indhira Santos, Erwin R. Tiongson, Carola Gruen, Natasha de Andrade Falcão, Gady Saiovici, Cesar A. Cancho|title=Back to Work: Growing with Jobs in Europe and Central Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xqrFAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&hl=no#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=World Bank Publications|year=2014|isbn=9780821399118|pages=86, 101}}</ref> In [[China]] a full 100% of employees were employed in the public sector by 1978, the year the [[Chinese economic reform]] was launched, after which the rates dropped to 56.4% in 1995, and to 32.8% in 2003.<ref name="Zeng">{{Cite book|author=Zeng, Jin|year=2013|title=State-Led Privatization in China: The Politics of Economic Reform|publisher=Routledge|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=TfUhAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&hl=no&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9781134464890|pages=52–53}}</ref>
In the OECD-countries, the average public sector employment rate was 21.3% in 2013.<ref name="OECD15"/>
